/*
Problem: Longest Subarray with Sum K

Given an array nums of size n and an integer k,
return the length of the longest subarray whose sum is equal to k.
*/

class Solution {
public:
    int longestSubarray(vector<int> &nums, int k) {
        unordered_map<long long, int> firstOccurrence;
        long long prefixSum = 0;
        int maxLength = 0;

        for (int i = 0; i < nums.size(); i++) {
            prefixSum += nums[i];

            if (prefixSum == k) {
                maxLength = i + 1;
            }

            if (firstOccurrence.find(prefixSum - k) != firstOccurrence.end()) {
                maxLength = max(maxLength, i - firstOccurrence[prefixSum - k]);
            }

            if (firstOccurrence.find(prefixSum) == firstOccurrence.end()) {
                firstOccurrence[prefixSum] = i;
            }
        }

        return maxLength;
    }
};

/*
Time Complexity: O(n)

Space Complexity: O(n)

My Mistakes / Misconceptions:
1. Used incorrect variable names (`a` instead of `nums` and undeclared `n`).
2. Used `p.end()` instead of `ps.end()`.
3. Calculated the subarray length incorrectly by treating the stored value as an array element instead of an index.
4. Forgot to handle the case when `prefixSum == k` (subarray starting from index 0).
5. Overwrote the first occurrence of a prefix sum instead of storing it only once.
Store the FIRST occurrence of each prefix sum.
   - The earliest index gives the maximum possible subarray length.
   - Never overwrite an existing prefix sum in the hashmap.
6. Initialized `maxLength` with `INT_MIN` instead of `0`.
7. Used `int` for prefix sum; `long long` is safer to avoid overflow.

Concepts Learned:
1. Prefix Sum
2. HashMap (unordered_map)
3. Longest Subarray with Sum K
4. Store only the first occurrence of each prefix sum.
5. If `(prefixSum - k)` exists, then the subarray from `previousIndex + 1` to the current index has sum `k`.
6. Always check if `prefixSum == k` to handle subarrays starting from index 0.

Possible Optimization:
- This is the optimal O(n) solution for arrays containing positive, negative, and zero values.
*/
